  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\n\r\nCurrently, the character limit for the usernames set in the ``RunAsUserName`` field is 20, which is too low, considering that \"ContainerAdministrator\" is a valid username and it is longer than 20 characters. A user should be able to run containers as Administrator, if needed.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nUsers should be able to spawn pods which run as ``ContainerAdministrator``.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n1. Enable WindowsRunAsUserName feature gate. (``kube-apiserver`` should have: ``--feature-gates=WindowsRunAsUserName=true``)\r\n2. ``kubectl create -f run-as-username.pod  # https://paste.ubuntu.com/p/KWTgZRnSpD/``\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n/sig windows\r\n/priority important-soon\r\n/milestone 1.16\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): 1.16\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration: N/A\r\n- OS (e.g: `cat /etc/os-release`): Windows Server 2019\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`): N/A\r\n- Install tools: N/A\r\n- Network plugin and version (if this is a network-related bug): N/A\r\n- Others:\r\n",
